notes: This report describes the history and general description, biological characteristics, recreational use, acquisition and development potential, proposed development and management, and acquisition recommendations for Franklin Lake. It is recommended part of Franklin Lake be added to the Ruby Lake Rational Wildlife Refuge. It has by far the best refuge potential of any area existing in eastern Nevada and with only limited development can probably surpass the existing Ruby Lake NWR in value to the waterfowl resource of the Pacific Flyway. The addition would benefit the rare and endangered species program by providing habitat for trumpeter swans and greater sandhill cranes. Development to take full advantage of available water is expected to increase waterfowl production (particularly mallards} pintails, gadwall, cinnamon-blue-winged teal, and redheads) and waterfowl migrational use* Increased public use in the forms of nature study, waterfowl hunting sari sightseeing will come as a result of improved access and increased wildlife populations. A tentative acquisition proposal, subject to change as a result of realty and engineering feasibility studies, is for a 14,000-acre refuge addition including the Raymond Gardiner and Walter Gardiner Ranches (including the lake lands claimed by them) and sufficient public domain land on the east side of Rranklin lake to create a manageable water area. Water and marsh within this area would total about 5,000 acres. These limits may need to be expanded to the north to secure additional water rights or to protect private landowners and the Government from possible water surpluses.
